  "prompt": "What are the best movies of the last two decades?",
  "response": "Okay, narrowing down the \"best\" movies of the last two decades (2004-2024) is a subjective and challenging task.  \"Best\" can mean different things to different people (best critically acclaimed, best box office, best culturally significant, or personally the most enjoyable).  I will provide a list that tries to balance critical acclaim, cultural impact, and lasting appeal, with a variety of genres represented.  I'll also break it down by era to make it more manageable.\n\n**Here's a selection, organized roughly chronologically within each era, with brief notes on why they're considered significant:**\n\n**2004-2009: A Period of Transition and Bold Filmmaking**\n\n*   **Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind (2004):**  Inventive, poignant, and thought-provoking exploration of memory, love, and loss.  Features stellar performances from Jim Carrey and Kate Winslet and a brilliant script by Charlie Kaufman.\n*   **Shaun of the Dead (2004):** Edgar Wright's breakout film. Blends horror and comedy in a way that's still refreshing and endlessly quotable. A definitive British cult classic.\n*   **Batman Begins (2005):** Christopher Nolan redefined the superhero genre with a grounded, realistic take on the Batman mythos. Kicked off a hugely influential trilogy.\n*   **Brokeback Mountain (2005):** Groundbreaking and moving film about a forbidden love in a repressed time. Had a huge cultural impact.\n*   **Children of Men (2006):** Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n's dystopian masterpiece is a technically brilliant and incredibly tense thriller with powerful social commentary.\n*   **Pan's Labyrinth (2006):** Guillermo del Toro's dark fantasy is a visually stunning and emotionally resonant fairy tale for adults, blending historical drama with fantastical elements.\n*   **The Departed (2006):** Martin Scorsese's return to crime thrillers, a remake of *Infernal Affairs*, with a stellar cast and a gripping plot.\n*   **No Country for Old Men (2007):** The Coen Brothers' masterful adaptation of Cormac McCarthy's novel is a neo-western thriller with unforgettable characters and a bleak, yet captivating, atmosphere.\n*   **There Will Be Blood (2007):** Paul Thomas Anderson's epic character study, anchored by Daniel Day-Lewis's tour-de-force performance. A dark, ambitious, and visually stunning film.\n*   **WALL-E (2008):** Pixar's near-silent masterpiece is a beautiful and poignant environmental allegory, with stunning animation and a heartwarming story.\n*   **The Dark Knight (2008):** Arguably the peak of the superhero genre, with Heath Ledger's iconic portrayal of the Joker. A dark, complex, and thrilling film.\n*   **Slumdog Millionaire (2008):** Danny Boyle's vibrant and uplifting film won hearts worldwide, with its rags-to-riches story and infectious energy.\n*   **Inglourious Basterds (2009):** Quentin Tarantino's gleefully revisionist WWII film is a stylish, violent, and wickedly funny masterpiece.\n*   **Avatar (2009):** James Cameron's groundbreaking visual spectacle revolutionized 3D filmmaking and became a global phenomenon.\n\n**2010-2019: Diverse Voices and Genre Evolution**\n\n*   **The Social Network (2010):** David Fincher's sharp and compelling drama about the rise of Facebook is a modern classic.\n*   **Inception (2010):** Christopher Nolan's mind-bending thriller is a visually stunning and intellectually stimulating film about dreams and reality.\n*   **Toy Story 3 (2010):** A perfect conclusion to the original trilogy. Pixar at its emotional best.\n*   **Black Swan (2010):** Darren Aronofsky's psychological thriller is a visually arresting and disturbing exploration of obsession and perfection.\n*   **The King's Speech (2010):** A moving and inspirational historical drama about King George VI's struggle with a stammer.\n*   **Drive (2011):** Stylish and atmospheric neo-noir. Established Nicolas Winding Refn as a distinctive director.\n*   **Melancholia (2011):** Lars von Trier's apocalyptic drama is a visually stunning and emotionally devastating film about depression and the end of the world.\n*   **The Artist (2011):** A charming and innovative silent film that won over audiences and critics alike.\n*   **Amour (2012):** Michael Haneke's unflinching and heartbreaking drama about aging and death.\n*   **Django Unchained (2012):** Quentin Tarantino's stylish and violent Western is a powerful and entertaining film about slavery and revenge.\n*   **Zero Dark Thirty (2012):** Kathryn Bigelow's tense and gripping thriller about the hunt for Osama bin Laden.\n*   **12 Years a Slave (2013):** Steve McQueen's harrowing and powerful historical drama about slavery in America.\n*   **Gravity (2013):** Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n's visually stunning and technically groundbreaking space thriller.\n*   **Her (2013):** Spike Jonze's thought-provoking and poignant sci-fi romance about a man who falls in love with an AI.\n*   **The Grand Budapest Hotel (2014):** Wes Anderson's visually stunning and whimsical comedy is a delightful and charming film.\n*   **Birdman or (The Unexpected Virtue of Ignorance) (2014):** Alejandro G. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu's innovative and ambitious film about an aging actor trying to revive his career.\n*   **Mad Max: Fury Road (2015):** George Miller's action masterpiece is a visually stunning and relentlessly thrilling film.\n*   **Spotlight (2015):** Tom McCarthy's gripping and important film about the Boston Globe's investigation into the Catholic Church sex abuse scandal.\n*   **Moonlight (2016):** Barry Jenkins's beautiful and moving coming-of-age story is a powerful and important film about identity, sexuality, and race.\n*   **La La Land (2016):** Damien Chazelle's vibrant and romantic musical is a visually stunning and emotionally resonant film.\n*   **Get Out (2017):** Jordan Peele's socially conscious horror film is a clever and terrifying satire on race relations in America.\n*   **Call Me By Your Name (2017):** Luca Guadagnino's sensual and evocative coming-of-age romance.\n*   **Dunkirk (2017):** Christopher Nolan's visceral and immersive war film is a stunning technical achievement.\n*   **Lady Bird (2017):** Greta Gerwig's charming and relatable coming-of-age story.\n*   **Roma (2018):** Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n's deeply personal and visually stunning film about a year in the life of a middle-class family in Mexico City.\n*   **Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse (2018):** A groundbreaking animated film with a unique visual style and a heartwarming story.\n*   **Parasite (2019):** Bong Joon-ho's darkly comedic thriller is a brilliant and biting satire on class inequality.\n*   **Portrait of a Lady on Fire (2019):** C\u00e9line Sciamma's historical romantic drama is a beautifully shot and emotionally resonant film.\n*   **Knives Out (2019):** Rian Johnson's clever and entertaining whodunit.\n\n**2020-2024: Streaming Era and Evolving Cinema**\n\n*   **Nomadland (2020):** Chlo\u00e9 Zhao's meditative and poignant film about a woman who travels the American West as a modern-day nomad.\n*   **Promising Young Woman (2020):** Emerald Fennell's darkly comedic and provocative thriller about a woman seeking revenge for her friend's sexual assault.\n*   **Soul (2020):** Pixar's thought-provoking and visually stunning film about life, death, and finding your purpose.\n*   **Judas and the Black Messiah (2021):** Shaka King's powerful and gripping historical drama about the betrayal of Fred Hampton.\n*   **The Power of the Dog (2021):** Jane Campion's slow-burn and visually stunning Western about repressed desire and toxic masculinity.\n*   **Drive My Car (2021):** Ryusuke Hamaguchi's moving and introspective film about grief, connection, and art.\n*   **Everything Everywhere All at Once (2022):** Daniel Kwan and Daniel Scheinert's mind-bending and genre-defying film about a Chinese-American woman who must save the multiverse.\n*   **The Banshees of Inisherin (2022):** Martin McDonagh's darkly comedic and melancholic film about the abrupt end of a friendship.\n*   **T\u00e1r (2022):** Todd Field's compelling and complex character study of a renowned conductor facing accusations of misconduct.\n*   **Aftersun (2022):** Charlotte Wells's moving and emotionally resonant debut film about a father-daughter vacation.\n*   **Oppenheimer (2023):** Christopher Nolan's epic biographical thriller about J. Robert Oppenheimer and the development of the atomic bomb.\n*   **Killers of the Flower Moon (2023):** Martin Scorsese's historical crime drama about the Osage Nation murders.\n* **Past Lives (2023):** Celine Song's deeply moving romance film.\n* **Anatomy of a Fall (2023):** Justine Triet's courtroom drama.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Personal Taste:** This list is a starting point. Your own \"best\" movies will depend on your personal preferences.\n*   **Genre Bias:**  I've tried to include a variety, but certain genres (like independent films or documentaries) might be underrepresented due to the difficulty of achieving widespread recognition.\n*   **Recency Bias:**  It's often easier to assess the impact of older films. The films from 2020-2024 still need time to solidify their place in cinematic history.\n*   **Availability:** The rise of streaming services has changed how we watch movies, and some films may be more accessible than others.\n\n**How to Find More:**\n\n*   **AFI's 100 Years...100 Movies (Anniversary Edition):** While focusing on American cinema, it's a good starting point for understanding influential films.\n*   **Sight & Sound Poll:** Conducted every ten years, this poll of film critics and directors offers a broader, more academic view.\n*   **Film Festivals:**  Cannes, Sundance, Venice, Toronto, etc., are great sources for discovering new and innovative films.\n*   **Reputable Critics:** Follow critics whose opinions you respect.\n\nThis list should give you a good foundation for exploring the best movies of the last two decades. Happy watching!\n",
